            Three additional neurorights proposed by Yuste and the NeuroRights Foundation (2017) and reinforced by UNESCO's 2025 Recommendation &mdash; <strong>equitable access to mental augmentation</strong>, <strong>protection from algorithmic bias</strong>, and <strong>free will</strong> &mdash; are not mapped in the threat taxonomy. These are distributive justice and governance concerns: no attack technique directly violates &ldquo;fair access,&rdquo; and algorithmic bias arises from systems processing neural data, not from attacks on the interface itself. Free will substantially overlaps with Cognitive Liberty in the context of threat-to-harm mappings. These rights are addressed at QIF's governance layer rather than the security layer. See <a href="/governance/">Governance &rarr; Neuroethics Alignment</a> for the full mapping.
          </p>
