      <section id="governance" class="mb-20">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold font-[family-name:var(--font-heading)] mb-6">7. Governance</h2>
        <div class="prose mb-8">
          <p>
            Each technique within the TARA atlas is assigned a consent tier reflecting the minimum regulatory oversight necessary for its deployment. These tiers are derived directly from NISS scores: higher biological impact, lower reversibility, and greater consent violation necessitate stricter governance.
          </p>
        </div>

        <ConsentTierChart />

        <div class="prose mt-8 mb-8">
          <p>
            The consent tier system aligns with existing regulatory frameworks:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>FDA 21 CFR Part 820 / 524B</strong> &mdash; Quality system requirements and cybersecurity expectations for medical devices</li>
            <li><strong>EU Medical Device Regulation (MDR) 2017/745</strong> &mdash; Post-market surveillance and clinical evaluation requirements</li>
            <li><strong>HIPAA</strong> &mdash; Neural signals constitute Protected Health Information (PHI) when linked to an individual. Raw EEG, decoded intentions, and cognitive state inferences all fall under the Security Rule and Breach Notification Rule. See the full <a href="/governance/REGULATORY_COMPLIANCE/">Regulatory Compliance Guide</a> for neural data classification</li>
            <li><strong>GDPR Article 9</strong> &mdash; Neural data is special category data (health data) under EU regulation, requiring explicit consent for processing. The right to erasure poses unique challenges for neural recordings</li>
            <li><strong>ISO 14971</strong> &mdash; Risk management for medical devices, mapped to NISS severity levels</li>
            <li><strong>IEC 62304</strong> &mdash; Software lifecycle for medical devices, with Runemate targeting Class C certification</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            These alignments are not merely aspirational. Each consent tier directly corresponds to specific regulatory obligations. An IRB-tier technique, for instance, mandates review processes equivalent to those governing invasive research protocols. A prohibited-tier technique is not merely categorized as "high risk" &mdash; it is explicitly ineligible for any clinical or research protocol under existing frameworks.
          </p>
        </div>

